00:01:46,110 --> 00:01:48,370
A confession.

4
00:01:48,380 --> 00:01:50,310
Is that what they call it?

5
00:02:05,560 --> 00:02:10,900
Billy Lyons was thrown in jail
for three days

6
00:02:10,900 --> 00:02:12,300
without cause.

7
00:02:16,070 --> 00:02:20,110
In the case of Inez Washington
v. the CR&L Bus Company,

8
00:02:20,110 --> 00:02:23,980
gentlemen, I have reviewed
all the papers and briefs in my chambers

9
00:02:23,980 --> 00:02:26,110
and I am prepared to rule.

10
00:02:26,110 --> 00:02:28,410
The court finds that
service of the complaint

11
00:02:28,420 --> 00:02:30,380
was in fact made at
the wrong address,

12
00:02:30,380 --> 00:02:32,620
as Attorney Friedman has argued.

13
00:02:32,620 --> 00:02:35,620
Therefore, the defendant's
motion to dismiss

14
00:02:35,620 --> 00:02:36,990
is granted.

15
00:02:36,990 --> 00:02:39,420
Thank you, Your Honor.

16
00:02:39,430 --> 00:02:41,390
Great work, Friedman.

17
00:02:44,430 --> 00:02:45,800
And to get their confession,

18
00:02:45,800 --> 00:02:47,400
Special Agent Cheatwood,

19
00:02:47,400 --> 00:02:49,770
sent by the governor himself,

20
00:02:49,770 --> 00:02:51,270
took this club...

21
00:02:51,270 --> 00:02:54,510
his "nigger beater,"
he called it.

22
00:02:54,510 --> 00:02:56,370
He tied Billy Lyons
to a chair...

23
00:02:58,310 --> 00:03:01,250
and he pounded Billy Lyons
in the head with it.

24
00:03:01,250 --> 00:03:03,750
And still Billy Lyons insisted

25
00:03:03,750 --> 00:03:05,750
he had not committed
these murders.

26
00:03:05,750 --> 00:03:08,650
We had this one
pegged as a loser.

27
00:03:08,660 --> 00:03:10,960
You've got a real knack
for spotting technicalities.

28
00:03:10,960 --> 00:03:12,520
Thank you,
Mr. Sprague.

29
00:03:15,930 --> 00:03:18,930
I'll be sending some more files your way,
if you've got the time.

30
00:03:18,930 --> 00:03:21,370
I will make the time.
Good.

31
00:03:24,200 --> 00:03:26,270
They forced him into their car

32
00:03:26,270 --> 00:03:28,570
and hauled him off
to the murder scene.

33
00:03:30,840 --> 00:03:34,210
The bodies had been burned
and were decomposing.

34
00:03:34,210 --> 00:03:36,810
They took some of the bones
of these dead bodies,

35
00:03:36,820 --> 00:03:40,490
put them in a pan and placed them
in Billy Lyons' hands.

36
00:03:40,490 --> 00:03:42,320
They admitted this.

37
00:03:42,320 --> 00:03:44,990
Delirious
with exhaustion and pain,

38
00:03:44,990 --> 00:03:48,890
Billy Lyons confessed to a crime
he did not commit.

39
00:03:48,900 --> 00:03:51,630
And it is based upon
that confession alone

40
00:03:51,630 --> 00:03:55,470
that they now seek to hang
Billy Lyons by the neck...

41
00:03:56,540 --> 00:03:57,970
until he is dead.

42
00:04:00,670 --> 00:04:04,410
You'll get them the next time, baby.
There may not be a next time.

43
00:04:04,410 --> 00:04:06,910
We needed this one.
All right.

44
00:04:06,910 --> 00:04:09,810
When you coming home?
I'll be on the next train to Knoxville.

45
00:04:09,820 --> 00:04:13,320
I should be home
by midday Wednesday.

46
00:04:13,320 --> 00:04:16,650
Okay. Be safe. I love you.
I love you too.

47
00:04:16,660 --> 00:04:18,460
Bye, baby.
See you soon.

48
00:04:26,870 --> 00:04:28,630
Hey, boy.

49
00:04:36,340 --> 00:04:39,140
Boy, what do you think
you're doing here?

50
00:04:44,280 --> 00:04:46,750
What you gonna do, nigger?

51
00:04:46,750 --> 00:04:49,620
All aboard.

52
00:04:49,620 --> 00:04:51,820
I'll see you boys another time.

53
00:04:53,290 --> 00:04:56,160
That son of a bitch.
Let's go scare him.

54
00:05:00,470 --> 00:05:01,930
Shoot him.

55
00:05:21,650 --> 00:05:24,060
NAACP.

56
00:05:24,060 --> 00:05:26,320
Please hold.

57
00:05:26,330 --> 00:05:28,730
Good morning, Mr. Marshall.
Good morning.

58
00:05:28,730 --> 00:05:30,630
Welcome back.
Thank you.

59
00:05:37,070 --> 00:05:39,770
Thurgood,
you're going to Bridgeport.

60
00:05:39,770 --> 00:05:42,310
What? Now?

61
00:05:42,310 --> 00:05:44,310
No, I swore to Buster
I would...

62
00:05:44,310 --> 00:05:47,180
How many Thurgoods are there?
Five or 10? There's only one.

63
00:05:47,180 --> 00:05:49,910
And that one is gonna get his ass
on the train tomorrow.

64
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:52,250
Why?
Why?

65
00:05:52,250 --> 00:05:54,850
"Nightmare in Greenwich."
That's why, Thurgood.

66
00:05:54,850 --> 00:05:58,990
"Wife Attacked by Negro Driver."
That's why, Thurgood.

67
00:05:58,990 --> 00:06:00,860
How about,
"Fear Grips Connecticut"?

68
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:02,530
What's the reaction?
Fear.

69
00:06:02,530 --> 00:06:05,830
Getting calls from all over the country.
Negroes getting fired.

70
00:06:05,830 --> 00:06:08,330
White families afraid
to have us in their home.

71
00:06:08,340 --> 00:06:11,800
If we can't work as domestics,
Negro families are going to starve.

72
00:06:11,810 --> 00:06:15,210
And this is a hell of a time
to lose half of our staff.

73
00:06:16,510 --> 00:06:18,910
It's got everything, doesn't it?

74
00:06:20,050 --> 00:06:22,680
"Eleanor Strubing,

75
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:24,880
fair-haired
Greenwich socialite,

76
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:28,220
was the victim of a beastly attack
in her own bedroom."

77
00:06:28,220 --> 00:06:32,860
Yes, and the boy that they're holding
is straight out of Native Son.

78
00:06:32,860 --> 00:06:34,790
Look at that.

79
00:06:34,790 --> 00:06:36,230
Wow.

80
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:39,030
"Joseph Spell.

81
00:06:40,330 --> 00:06:43,470
Uneducated Negro servant
with a criminal past."

82
00:06:43,470 --> 00:06:47,640
A fable that the New York City press
is gonna feed on to the last morsel.

83
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:50,510
Yeah. They're starving for this one.
So are we.

84
00:06:50,510 --> 00:06:54,110
We win this thing, our big donors
are coming right back, Thurgood.

85
00:06:55,810 --> 00:06:58,820
There's only 13 million Negroes
depending on you.

86
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:17,700
Irwin said
I would find you here.

87
00:07:17,700 --> 00:07:19,570
What?

88
00:07:19,570 --> 00:07:23,010
Your brother said I would find you here.
You know, swimming.

89
00:07:24,080 --> 00:07:26,540
Nice swimsuit.

90
00:07:26,550 --> 00:07:29,710
Who the hell are you?
Tad Lancaster.

91
00:07:29,720 --> 00:07:31,120
Bridgeport High.
Remember?

92
00:07:31,120 --> 00:07:33,720
Trombone?
Yeah!

93
00:07:33,720 --> 00:07:36,790
Still blowin' it too, man.
What are you doing here, Tad?

94
00:07:36,790 --> 00:07:41,930
Oh, I am, uh, working
with the Bridgeport NAACP.

95
00:07:41,930 --> 00:07:45,300
Actually, I am the Bridgeport NAACP,
and I need a little favor.

96
00:07:45,300 --> 00:07:47,230
Do you know that Spell case?

97
00:07:47,230 --> 00:07:51,100
The guy who attacked the
girl from Greenwich? Yeah.

98
00:07:51,100 --> 00:07:55,070
Now, National is sending a lawyer from
the city to handle his defense,

99
00:07:55,070 --> 00:07:57,540
and we need a local guy
to get him admitted.

100
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:04,950
Uh, sorry, no.
I'm not gonna do that.

101
00:08:04,950 --> 00:08:07,620
- There's nothing else required.
- I'm not interested.

102
00:08:07,620 --> 00:08:10,620
Think about the publicity.
That's exactly what I'm thinking of.

103
00:08:10,620 --> 00:08:13,220
- Your brother seems to think...
- My brother is an absolute idiot.

104
00:08:13,230 --> 00:08:16,290
Listen, Tad, thank you so much
for thinking of me.

105
00:08:16,300 --> 00:08:18,500
Honestly, I'm grateful.

106
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:20,830
But I don't handle
criminal cases. Okay?

107
00:08:20,830 --> 00:08:23,200
Find someone who wants
that kind of attention.

108
00:08:24,940 --> 00:08:26,870
Irwin already filed the papers
with the court.

109
00:08:29,140 --> 00:08:31,310
He did what?

110
00:08:31,310 --> 00:08:33,780
...scattered
over many parts of the country.

111
00:08:33,780 --> 00:08:38,580
Nazi aircraft were reported over the
south coast, the midlands... Paper, please.

112
00:08:38,590 --> 00:08:40,490
As well as over the London area.

113
00:08:40,490 --> 00:08:42,620
Thurgood Marshall.

114
00:08:42,620 --> 00:08:45,120
National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People.

115
00:08:45,120 --> 00:08:48,290
Sam Friedman.
Um, Friedman and Friedman.

116
00:08:48,290 --> 00:08:49,760
Good to meet you, Sam.

117
00:08:49,760 --> 00:08:52,160
Give me a hand with these, would you?
Sure.

118
00:08:54,770 --> 00:08:56,630
What have you got in here?
Cement?

119
00:08:56,640 --> 00:08:58,240
Guns.

120
00:08:59,140 --> 00:09:00,640
Books, Mr. Friedman.

121
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:03,010
My law library.

122
00:09:03,010 --> 00:09:05,010
It goes where I go.

123
00:09:05,010 --> 00:09:08,510
Look, I told Tad Lancaster
I'll get you admitted, as a favor.

124
00:09:08,520 --> 00:09:11,820
But I can't get involved with a
case like this. Yeah? Why not?

125
00:09:11,820 --> 00:09:15,550
Well, I do insurance defense.
You know, accident cases.

126
00:09:15,560 --> 00:09:17,560
I've got a reputation
to think of.

127
00:09:17,560 --> 00:09:19,720
Ah.

128
00:09:19,730 --> 00:09:22,390
That must be difficult.
What?

129
00:09:22,400 --> 00:09:25,960
Having a reputation to think of.

130
00:09:25,970 --> 00:09:29,300
You meet our client yet?
Your client. And no, I was waiting...

131
00:09:29,300 --> 00:09:31,570
Well, come on then.
Let's get to it.

132
00:09:37,010 --> 00:09:38,810
Got another one coming in.
Okay.

133
00:09:38,810 --> 00:09:40,880
University of Maryland
Law School.

134
00:09:40,880 --> 00:09:42,750
Was walking distance from home.

135
00:09:42,750 --> 00:09:46,480
But they didn't accept colored,
so I had to go to Howard.

136
00:09:46,490 --> 00:09:48,520
An hour and a half
each way by bus,

137
00:09:48,520 --> 00:09:50,820
and well-known
as a school for failures.

138
00:09:50,820 --> 00:09:52,690
That's too bad.

139
00:09:52,690 --> 00:09:57,230
No. No, it was the best thing
that ever happened to me.

140
00:09:57,230 --> 00:10:00,530
They'd just brought in a new dean,
Charles Hamilton Houston.

141
00:10:00,530 --> 00:10:03,730
Turned that place around,
taught me everything I know,

142
00:10:03,740 --> 00:10:06,070
including how to sue
the University of Maryland.

143
00:10:06,070 --> 00:10:08,110
You sued them?

144
00:10:08,110 --> 00:10:11,580
You bet your ass I did.
Soon as I passed the bar.

145
00:10:12,680 --> 00:10:14,110
And?

146
00:10:16,680 --> 00:10:18,980
Supreme Court ordered the bastards
to integrate.

147
00:10:23,020 --> 00:10:25,720
You argued in the United States
Supreme Court?

148
00:10:25,730 --> 00:10:27,630
What?

149
00:10:27,630 --> 00:10:29,990
No, the Maryland Supreme Court.

150
00:10:32,760 --> 00:10:35,280
I didn't argue in front
of the US Supreme Court until last year.

151
00:10:36,300 --> 00:10:37,800
Your boy is ready for you.

152
00:10:54,150 --> 00:10:57,150
Spell.
Lawyer's here to see you.

153
00:11:11,570 --> 00:11:15,940
Mr. Spell, I'm Thurgood Marshall
with the NAACP.

154
00:11:15,940 --> 00:11:17,840
You heard of us?

155
00:11:20,110 --> 00:11:22,950
- You a lawyer?
- I am.

156
00:11:22,950 --> 00:11:25,450
This is Sam Friedman.
He's a lawyer too.

157
00:11:25,450 --> 00:11:28,690
You can go.
Got no money for lawyers.

158
00:11:28,690 --> 00:11:30,660
Anybody ask you for money?

159
00:11:32,190 --> 00:11:34,160
Did you rape that woman, Joseph?

160
00:11:34,160 --> 00:11:35,790
No.

161
00:11:35,800 --> 00:11:38,360
Why does she say you did?
I don't know.

162
00:11:38,360 --> 00:11:40,530
She says you raped her
and tried to kill her.

163
00:11:40,540 --> 00:11:41,540
She's lying.

164
00:11:42,430 --> 00:11:44,540
I was up in White Plains,
at a club.

165
00:11:44,540 --> 00:11:47,340
Come on, Joseph.
All night long?

166
00:11:47,340 --> 00:11:50,040
No, not all night.

167
00:11:50,040 --> 00:11:53,540
I was at the house but couldn't sleep,
so I went to play cards.

168
00:11:53,550 --> 00:11:56,550
Got back
maybe 6:00, 6:30.

169
00:11:56,550 --> 00:11:58,780
Anybody see you at the club?

170
00:11:58,790 --> 00:12:01,850
Yeah, but I don't know
their names or nothin'.

171
00:12:01,850 --> 00:12:05,290
For an alibi defense,
you need witnesses, Joseph.

172
00:12:05,290 --> 00:12:07,960
Otherwise it's her word
against yours.

173
00:12:07,960 --> 00:12:10,430
And who do you think
they're gonna believe?

174
00:12:11,200 --> 00:12:13,130
There was a cop.

175
00:12:15,300 --> 00:12:18,840
A cop? Stopped me in Port Chester
on the way to the club.

176
00:12:18,840 --> 00:12:21,540
Looked at my license, then let me go.
What time was that?

177
00:12:21,540 --> 00:12:25,110
I don't know.
Maybe 3:00 in the morning.

178
00:12:26,910 --> 00:12:29,980
I'm telling you this up front.

179
00:12:29,980 --> 00:12:33,420
The NAACP,
we're not like most lawyers.

180
00:12:33,420 --> 00:12:35,490
We only represent
innocent people,

181
00:12:35,490 --> 00:12:37,490
people accused
because of their race.

182
00:12:37,490 --> 00:12:39,960
That's our mission.
You understand?

183
00:12:41,490 --> 00:12:43,730
So I need to know this...
Look at me now.

184
00:12:45,160 --> 00:12:47,000
Did you do
what they said you did?

185
00:12:49,030 --> 00:12:51,470
I never touched that woman.

186
00:12:54,170 --> 00:12:56,440
Okay, Joseph.

187
00:12:56,440 --> 00:12:57,440
You got lawyers now.

188
00:13:13,090 --> 00:13:15,060
Go ahead.
Change the station.

189
00:13:17,360 --> 00:13:20,200
What do you know
about the prosecutor?

190
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:22,200
Lorin Willis.

191
00:13:22,200 --> 00:13:24,800
Graduated Yale
the day he was born.

192
00:13:24,800 --> 00:13:27,400
Unless you came over on the Mayflower,
you're nothing to him.

193
00:13:27,410 --> 00:13:30,410
They're grooming him
to be senator, I hear.

194
00:13:30,410 --> 00:13:33,310
What do you know about the judge?
Judge Foster?

195
00:13:35,110 --> 00:13:37,180
Former law partner
of Willis's father.

196
00:13:46,490 --> 00:13:49,390
I'll move
your admission Monday morning, and then...

197
00:13:49,400 --> 00:13:52,260
Back to fighting off
those insurance claims.

198
00:13:52,270 --> 00:13:54,030
Yeah, I know.

199
00:14:08,610 --> 00:14:11,850
Ah. So you like
Langston Hughes, huh?

200
00:14:11,850 --> 00:14:13,580
Of course.
Don't you?

201
00:14:13,590 --> 00:14:16,450
I don't give a damn
about no poetry.

202
00:14:16,460 --> 00:14:19,020
Come on.

203
00:14:19,030 --> 00:14:21,830
I actually went to school
with Langston.

204
00:14:21,830 --> 00:14:24,960
I just wish he'd do something
more worthwhile with his time.

205
00:14:24,960 --> 00:14:28,170
Another bourbon, Mr. Marshall?
Sure.

206
00:14:28,170 --> 00:14:31,970
You know, Tad's got a law degree too.
From Fordham.

207
00:14:31,970 --> 00:14:35,110
You told me you were a driver.
Yep.

208
00:14:35,110 --> 00:14:39,980
The state of Connecticut decided to
not allow me a license to practice law.

209
00:14:39,980 --> 00:14:43,180
They were generous enough
to give me a driver's license, however.

210
00:14:43,980 --> 00:14:46,820
I see.

211
00:14:46,820 --> 00:14:48,950
What about you, Irene?

212
00:14:48,960 --> 00:14:51,820
What are you gonna be when you grow up?
A nurse like your mother?

213
00:14:51,820 --> 00:14:54,390
No.
A lawyer then?

214
00:14:54,390 --> 00:14:57,860
No.
A fighter pilot.

215
00:14:57,860 --> 00:14:59,960
A fighter pilot?

216
00:15:01,370 --> 00:15:04,700
Well, I feel a whole lot
more safe knowing that.

217
00:15:04,700 --> 00:15:08,110
All right, say good night
to Mr. Marshall, Renie.

218
00:15:09,340 --> 00:15:11,310
Good night.

219
00:15:11,310 --> 00:15:13,910
You got kids?

220
00:15:13,910 --> 00:15:17,250
Uh, Buster and I have been trying
for a while.

221
00:15:17,250 --> 00:15:21,190
Buster is my wife. Sometimes people
think I'm talking about my dog.

222
00:15:21,190 --> 00:15:24,820
You should get a dog and name it "Mrs.
Marshall." Ah!

223
00:15:24,820 --> 00:15:27,760
So, you think this boy did it?

224
00:15:29,090 --> 00:15:31,060
Hey, whose side you on?

225
00:15:31,060 --> 00:15:34,830
Women don't just go around
lying about being raped, Mr. Marshall.

226
00:15:34,830 --> 00:15:37,740
You're going to have to figure out
why she'd do such a thing.

227
00:15:37,740 --> 00:15:40,240
Burden of proof is on the State.
Is it now?

228
00:15:40,240 --> 00:15:42,870
Hey there.

229
00:15:42,880 --> 00:15:45,780
So what can you tell me
about this Friedman guy anyway?

230
00:15:45,780 --> 00:15:48,950
Sam and me played trombone together
in the high school band.

231
00:15:48,950 --> 00:15:51,520
You trust him? Sam? Oh, yeah.
Yeah, yeah.

232
00:15:51,520 --> 00:15:55,620
If you dropped a nickel while kicking him
in the balls, he'd return it to you.

233
00:15:55,620 --> 00:15:57,690
Mmm.

234
00:15:59,260 --> 00:16:01,790
Couldn't play trombone
for shit though.

235
00:16:01,790 --> 00:16:04,760
Gentlemen! Can I have a minute, please?

236
00:16:04,760 --> 00:16:07,400
Just a minute!
Who is this, a relative of Spell?

237
00:16:07,400 --> 00:16:09,870
I'm Mr. Spell's attorney.
Thurgood Marshall.

238
00:16:09,870 --> 00:16:11,440
I thought you were
Spell's lawyer, Mr. Freeman.

239
00:16:11,440 --> 00:16:15,440
It's Friedman.
Sam Friedman.

240
00:16:15,440 --> 00:16:18,110
Of Friedman and Friedman.
Local counsel. That is all.

241
00:16:18,110 --> 00:16:20,580
- The defense team, huh?
- Is your boy innocent, Mr. Friedman?

242
00:16:20,580 --> 00:16:25,080
He is not my... Let me state this to
you all clearly and unequivocally.

243
00:16:25,080 --> 00:16:28,990
Our client, Joseph Spell,
is an innocent man.

244
00:16:28,990 --> 00:16:31,520
Well, let's get
a picture of you two.

245
00:17:00,620 --> 00:17:02,050
All rise.

246
00:17:03,420 --> 00:17:05,660
Superior Court
is now in session.

247
00:17:05,660 --> 00:17:08,760
The Honorable Carl Foster
presiding.

248
00:17:13,330 --> 00:17:16,100
You may be seated.

249
00:17:18,500 --> 00:17:22,210
The State of Connecticut
v. Joseph Spell.

250
00:17:22,210 --> 00:17:24,140
Are the parties
ready to proceed?

251
00:17:24,140 --> 00:17:26,340
The State is ready,
Your Honor.

252
00:17:26,350 --> 00:17:29,010
Ah, Mr. Willis.
Good morning.

253
00:17:29,020 --> 00:17:30,980
How's your father doing?

254
00:17:30,980 --> 00:17:33,780
He's better. Thank you.
That's kind of you to ask.

255
00:17:35,320 --> 00:17:38,360
Uh, the defense is ready as well,
Your Honor.

256
00:17:38,360 --> 00:17:40,260
Well then, let's get on with it.

257
00:17:41,330 --> 00:17:43,460
Mr., uh...

258
00:17:43,460 --> 00:17:45,560
Mr. Friedman.

259
00:17:45,560 --> 00:17:48,730
You filed an application to admit
an out-of-state attorney?

260
00:17:48,730 --> 00:17:52,570
Yes, Your Honor. Attorney Thurgood
Marshall of the Maryland Bar.

261
00:17:52,570 --> 00:17:55,710
I have the application
in front of me, Mr. Friedman.

262
00:17:55,710 --> 00:17:58,110
Uh-huh.

263
00:18:00,350 --> 00:18:03,880
Why do we need to admit this lawyer,
Mr. Friedman?

264
00:18:03,880 --> 00:18:06,580
Does he have a long-standing relationship
with the defendant?

265
00:18:06,590 --> 00:18:08,720
Uh, no, Your Honor,
uh, but...

266
00:18:08,720 --> 00:18:11,660
- How long has he known him?
- Not long, Your Honor, but...

267
00:18:11,660 --> 00:18:13,260
Exactly how long?

268
00:18:14,730 --> 00:18:18,400
Well, he met him for the first time
a few days ago.

269
00:18:18,400 --> 00:18:20,360
However...

270
00:18:20,370 --> 00:18:22,600
A few days ago?

271
00:18:22,600 --> 00:18:26,600
Well, then what possible reason
could there be to admit him?

272
00:18:26,610 --> 00:18:30,410
You're a perfectly capable attorney,
are you not, Mr. Friedman?

273
00:18:30,410 --> 00:18:32,840
You have tried cases before,
haven't you?

274
00:18:32,850 --> 00:18:36,250
Only civil cases, Your Honor.
But Mr. Marshall is with the NAACP.

275
00:18:36,250 --> 00:18:39,520
And they are concerned that their defendant
receive a fair trial.

276
00:18:39,520 --> 00:18:42,290
So are we all,
Attorney Friedman.

277
00:18:42,290 --> 00:18:43,920
So are we all.

278
00:18:43,920 --> 00:18:45,890
But he's not a member
of our bar, is he?

279
00:18:45,890 --> 00:18:47,790
No, he's not.

280
00:18:47,790 --> 00:18:50,790
However, Your Honor,
Mr. Marshall is a respected attorney.

281
00:18:50,800 --> 00:18:52,960
He argued in the United States
Supreme Court.

282
00:18:52,970 --> 00:18:54,870
That has no bearing
on this case.

283
00:18:54,870 --> 00:18:56,770
Your Honor, may I be heard?

284
00:18:56,770 --> 00:18:58,970
No, you may not.

285
00:19:00,240 --> 00:19:02,040
The court has heard enough
and will rule.

286
00:19:06,440 --> 00:19:08,480
The court sees
no legal requirement

287
00:19:08,480 --> 00:19:10,750
to admit out-of-state counsel
in this case.

288
00:19:10,750 --> 00:19:13,050
But, Your Honor...
However,

289
00:19:13,050 --> 00:19:16,120
the court not only wishes to be fair
to all of the parties,

290
00:19:16,120 --> 00:19:19,560
but to maintain the appearance of fairness
as well.

291
00:19:19,560 --> 00:19:22,630
Therefore, the court
will allow Mr. Marshall

292
00:19:22,630 --> 00:19:24,660
to enter his appearance
for the defense...

293
00:19:24,660 --> 00:19:26,060
Respectfully...

294
00:19:26,070 --> 00:19:29,330
His written appearance,
Mr. Willis.

295
00:19:29,340 --> 00:19:32,140
Mr. Marshall
may sit at counsel table.

296
00:19:32,140 --> 00:19:35,470
However, he may not speak.

297
00:19:35,470 --> 00:19:38,110
Your Honor,
I must speak for the client.

298
00:19:38,110 --> 00:19:41,650
He may not speak, argue,
or examine witnesses.

299
00:19:41,650 --> 00:19:45,780
If he violates this ruling,
he will be held in contempt of court.

300
00:19:45,780 --> 00:19:48,120
And you as well,
Mr. Friedman.

301
00:19:48,120 --> 00:19:50,490
You will conduct this case.

302
00:19:50,490 --> 00:19:52,820
Me?
Yes, you.

303
00:19:52,830 --> 00:19:55,930
The trial will begin
a month from today

304
00:19:55,930 --> 00:19:57,030
at 10:00 a.m.

305
00:19:58,100 --> 00:19:59,500
Court adjourned.

306
00:19:59,500 --> 00:20:02,030
All rise.

307
00:20:02,030 --> 00:20:03,530
What the...

308
00:20:03,540 --> 00:20:05,940
What the hell just happened?

309
00:20:05,940 --> 00:20:09,140
What just happened here?
Shut up and be quiet. Let me think.

310
00:20:09,140 --> 00:20:11,040
I can't do this. You know that.
Shut up.

311
00:20:11,040 --> 00:20:12,610
Excuse me?

312
00:20:15,650 --> 00:20:17,250
That son of a bitch.

313
00:20:19,280 --> 00:20:23,120
I've tried cases before judges
who were Grand Dragons of the Ku Klux Klan,

314
00:20:23,120 --> 00:20:25,790
who forced me to enter
through the back door,

315
00:20:25,790 --> 00:20:27,820
but this horseshit is a first.

316
00:20:27,830 --> 00:20:30,290
I cannot get involved
in a case like this.

317
00:20:30,300 --> 00:20:32,860
Are you listening to me?
It would destroy my practice.

318
00:20:32,870 --> 00:20:34,900
This is not my problem.

319
00:20:34,900 --> 00:20:36,270
The hell it isn't.

320
00:20:38,340 --> 00:20:41,410
No, you heard the judge.

321
00:20:41,410 --> 00:20:45,080
Until we can find somebody better,
it's you and me.

322
00:20:48,310 --> 00:20:49,980
It's our problem now.

323
00:20:51,050 --> 00:20:52,880
Uh, Mr. Marshall...

324
00:21:09,370 --> 00:21:11,270
According to
Eleanor Strubing's account,

325
00:21:11,270 --> 00:21:16,240
Spell rapes her at home,
ties and gags her, then drives up here.

326
00:21:16,240 --> 00:21:20,010
He stops approximately 60 feet
onto the bridge, like so...

327
00:21:20,010 --> 00:21:23,350
Joseph! Please!

328
00:21:23,350 --> 00:21:25,320
Takes her out of the car...

329
00:21:26,450 --> 00:21:28,820
No! No!

330
00:21:30,360 --> 00:21:32,220
then pushes her
over the guardrail,

331
00:21:32,220 --> 00:21:34,360
into the reservoir,
right about here.

332
00:21:38,900 --> 00:21:42,800
He throws rocks at her,
then drives away.

333
00:21:42,800 --> 00:21:44,700
Somehow she gets to shore.

334
00:21:46,240 --> 00:21:48,470
Dripping wet.

335
00:21:48,470 --> 00:21:50,810
Then climbs up to the road.

336
00:22:00,920 --> 00:22:02,390
Ah.

337
00:22:03,820 --> 00:22:05,960
Awfully scary down there though.

338
00:22:09,730 --> 00:22:11,700
Go take a look
where she climbed out.

339
00:22:13,060 --> 00:22:15,200
Me? These are
my best shoes.

340
00:22:17,240 --> 00:22:20,170
Please try to
make yourself useful.

341
00:23:06,520 --> 00:23:08,650
Stop. Stop!

342
00:23:10,560 --> 00:23:12,120
Stop.

343
00:23:13,990 --> 00:23:16,960
This is where
the truck driver found her.

344
00:23:28,570 --> 00:23:30,310
What do you want with those?

345
00:23:30,310 --> 00:23:33,880
It's an old Negro superstition.

346
00:23:33,880 --> 00:23:36,480
Always take a little piece
of the earth with you.

347
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:38,380
Really?

348
00:23:49,660 --> 00:23:52,800
Mr. Friedman, your picture's
on the front page with Mr. Marshall.

349
00:23:56,500 --> 00:23:59,700
Oh.
Not a bad picture.

350
00:23:59,710 --> 00:24:01,710
Of me, anyway.

351
00:24:01,710 --> 00:24:05,040
- Also, your wife called.
- Oh, Sam. Perfect.

352
00:24:05,040 --> 00:24:05,790
Where you been?

353
00:24:05,800 --> 00:24:08,080
Out getting the cutlery
I need to castrate you.

354
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:10,580
You must be Irwin.
I am.

355
00:24:10,580 --> 00:24:12,520
Mr. Marshall. Pleasure to meet you.
Pleasure.

356
00:24:12,520 --> 00:24:14,580
Sam, listen, I have great news.

357
00:24:14,590 --> 00:24:16,950
I made some calls.
Harry Gruber, he wants the case.

358
00:24:16,960 --> 00:24:19,560
Harry Gruber.
The Communist.

359
00:24:19,560 --> 00:24:21,760
Sam, at least he handles
criminal defense.

360
00:24:28,300 --> 00:24:30,400
Can you get Gruber
on the line, Ruth?

361
00:24:30,400 --> 00:24:31,940
Sure thing.
Thank you.

362
00:24:31,940 --> 00:24:34,600
This is not
a cut-and-dry case.

363
00:24:34,610 --> 00:24:38,940
You should really consider whether or not
this is something you want to commit to.

364
00:24:38,940 --> 00:24:41,210
You want the Communist Party
taking over?

365
00:24:41,210 --> 00:24:43,380
They'll martyr Spell
for their own cause.

366
00:24:43,380 --> 00:24:45,650
Not my problem.

367
00:24:45,650 --> 00:24:48,750
You think he did it.
That's for a jury to decide.

368
00:24:48,750 --> 00:24:53,160
You think he raped this woman
and drove her to the reservoir to kill her?

369
00:24:53,160 --> 00:24:55,830
People have done
stranger things.

370
00:24:55,830 --> 00:24:59,460
That's right. People do all sorts
of strange things, horrible things.

371
00:24:59,470 --> 00:25:03,000
But throw a woman over the bridge, into the
water, not check to see if she's dead,

372
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:05,170
then drive back to her house?

373
00:25:05,170 --> 00:25:07,640
You've gotta have a pretty dim view
of Negroes

374
00:25:07,640 --> 00:25:10,810
to think any one of us would do anything
so goddamn stupid.

375
00:25:16,780 --> 00:25:20,020
The papers say he was dishonorably
discharged from the army.

376
00:25:20,020 --> 00:25:22,590
This isn't
a court-martial.

377
00:25:22,590 --> 00:25:24,650
He was fired from his last job
for stealing.

378
00:25:24,660 --> 00:25:26,620
No charges were brought.

379
00:25:26,630 --> 00:25:30,330
He left behind a wife
and two kids in Louisiana, Thurgood.

380
00:25:30,330 --> 00:25:33,530
Yes, he's got baggage.
Criminal defendants usually do.

381
00:25:33,530 --> 00:25:36,770
They're not perfect citizens
like you and me.

382
00:25:36,770 --> 00:25:39,500
But none of that makes him guilty
of this crime.

383
00:25:39,510 --> 00:25:42,640
I got Gruber on the phone.
What do you want me to tell him?

384
00:25:42,640 --> 00:25:44,670
I don't know.
Tell him he's a schmuck.

385
00:25:44,680 --> 00:25:47,510
- Sam, come on.
- Irwin! Genug, huh?

386
00:25:49,820 --> 00:25:52,480
Why me?

387
00:25:52,480 --> 00:25:54,820
I need someone who will do
as I say.

388
00:25:54,820 --> 00:25:57,350
What makes you think
I will do as you say?

389
00:25:57,360 --> 00:26:00,160
You have no choice.
You don't know what you're doing.

390
00:26:00,160 --> 00:26:02,530
You're quite a salesman.

391
00:26:02,530 --> 00:26:04,190
There's no time for that.

392
00:26:06,630 --> 00:26:09,000
You want me to try this case.

393
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:12,300
No, I need you to try this case.

394
00:26:13,970 --> 00:26:17,670
"And the Lord commanded Moses
to enlist his brother's help.

395
00:26:17,680 --> 00:26:19,910
He shall speak for you
to the people."

396
00:26:19,910 --> 00:26:21,880
"He shall be your mouth,

397
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:24,210
and you shall be
as God to him."

398
00:26:32,260 --> 00:26:34,120
Tell Gruber to go fuck himself.

399
00:26:34,860 --> 00:26:36,530
All right.

400
00:26:36,530 --> 00:26:39,160
And find the cop who stopped Spell.
We need a witness.

401
00:26:39,160 --> 00:26:41,100
Okay. I'm on it.

402
00:26:44,770 --> 00:26:46,740
What is this?

403
00:26:46,740 --> 00:26:50,210
You say you've never tried
a criminal case before, right?

404
00:26:50,210 --> 00:26:52,110
Yeah, that's right.

405
00:26:52,110 --> 00:26:53,390
You'd better start reading then.

406
00:26:56,580 --> 00:26:58,180
You've got one month.

407
00:27:09,460 --> 00:27:12,760
Hey, look who's back.
You coming tonight?

408
00:27:12,760 --> 00:27:14,930
No, not tonight.

409
00:27:14,930 --> 00:27:18,030
Oh, man, I was really looking forward
to catching up with you.

410
00:27:20,810 --> 00:27:24,540
All right, you need to stop feeling sorry
for yourself.

411
00:27:24,540 --> 00:27:26,910
I am the one who's been sick...

412
00:27:26,910 --> 00:27:28,350
every morning...

413
00:27:29,580 --> 00:27:30,980
for the past month.

414
00:27:30,980 --> 00:27:32,880
What?

415
00:27:32,880 --> 00:27:35,950
You better not be lying.
Look at the bump.

416
00:27:35,950 --> 00:27:38,460
Oh! I see it.

417
00:27:38,460 --> 00:27:40,220
You see it?
Mmm!

418
00:27:41,460 --> 00:27:43,660
Mmm, mmm.

419
00:27:43,660 --> 00:27:45,630
I'm not going anywhere
after this.

420
00:27:45,630 --> 00:27:47,160
Hmm.

421
00:27:47,170 --> 00:27:48,900
What?

422
00:27:48,900 --> 00:27:51,570
You don't believe me.
No, I don't.

423
00:27:51,570 --> 00:27:53,500
I swear.

424
00:27:53,510 --> 00:27:55,110
You swear.

425
00:27:55,110 --> 00:27:57,670
I swear I swear.
Nowhere, nowhere.

426
00:27:57,680 --> 00:27:59,580
I swear.
Mmm!

427
00:28:07,250 --> 00:28:10,020
♪ Trouble in mind ♪

428
00:28:10,020 --> 00:28:11,860
♪ Guess I'm blue ♪

429
00:28:14,190 --> 00:28:16,760
♪ But I won't be blue always ♪

430
00:28:16,760 --> 00:28:19,260
♪ Sun is gonna shine ♪

431
00:28:19,260 --> 00:28:21,230
♪ In my back door someday ♪

432
00:28:22,970 --> 00:28:25,500
Langston, he swore
on his mother's life

433
00:28:25,500 --> 00:28:28,140
that he wouldn't be going
anywhere anytime soon.

434
00:28:28,140 --> 00:28:31,510
My mother's name was never mentioned.

435
00:28:31,510 --> 00:28:35,110
Well, this case is all anybody in this city
is talking about.

436
00:28:35,110 --> 00:28:38,850
Which only means that the inevitable loss
will be that much more devastating.

437
00:28:38,850 --> 00:28:41,850
Don't bet against me.
You're not even trying the case, baby.

438
00:28:41,850 --> 00:28:45,060
Every single word that man
utters in that courtroom will be mine.

439
00:28:45,060 --> 00:28:48,020
I'm just making the point
that a Negro charged with ravishment

440
00:28:48,030 --> 00:28:49,890
by the Greenwich gentility

441
00:28:49,900 --> 00:28:53,300
should probably save himself the time
and unpleasantness of a trial.

442
00:28:53,300 --> 00:28:55,670
Langston, maybe you should
just go back to Spain.

443
00:28:55,670 --> 00:28:58,030
Or back to Russia.

444
00:28:58,040 --> 00:29:02,070
Write your little poems,
explore big ideas with your comrades.

445
00:29:02,070 --> 00:29:04,710
I was fighting Fascists
in Spain.

446
00:29:04,710 --> 00:29:07,680
Well, you were writing about
fighting Fascists in Spain.

447
00:29:07,680 --> 00:29:10,380
Listen, by the time the baby comes,

448
00:29:10,380 --> 00:29:13,080
Thurgood's gonna be
out of a job.

449
00:29:13,090 --> 00:29:16,320
Do none of you
have any confidence in me?

450
00:29:16,320 --> 00:29:19,090
I'd say you have enough confidence
for us all,

451
00:29:19,090 --> 00:29:21,090
misplaced as it may be.

452
00:29:23,100 --> 00:29:26,000
Great to see you!

453
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:28,230
God, here comes Zora.

454
00:29:28,230 --> 00:29:30,230
Probably leaving dinner
with Charles Lindbergh.

455
00:29:30,240 --> 00:29:32,370
- Don't you dare...
- Zora!

456
00:29:32,370 --> 00:29:34,070
Sit down!

457
00:29:34,070 --> 00:29:36,070
Come on over here.

458
00:29:36,070 --> 00:29:38,680
Zora Neale Hurston!
Hi!

459
00:29:38,680 --> 00:29:39,980
How y'all doin'?

460
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:43,610
Langston Hughes.
Zora.

461
00:29:44,450 --> 00:29:45,680
Mmm.

462
00:29:50,360 --> 00:29:53,020
- And who is this?
- I'm August.

463
00:29:53,020 --> 00:29:55,230
- I've heard so much about you.
- Huh.

464
00:29:55,230 --> 00:29:58,360
That's funny, 'cause I haven't heard
a thing about you.

465
00:29:58,360 --> 00:30:00,230
Huh, Langston?

466
00:30:00,230 --> 00:30:02,600
♪ Oh, trouble in mind ♪

467
00:30:10,980 --> 00:30:12,510
You had it now, girl!

468
00:30:17,950 --> 00:30:20,350
Okay, guys.
We ready to go?

469
00:30:25,890 --> 00:30:28,460
You're still not talking to me.

470
00:30:28,460 --> 00:30:30,830
It's...
It's not my fault.

471
00:30:30,830 --> 00:30:34,130
You have no idea how persuasive
this guy can be.

472
00:30:51,650 --> 00:30:53,650
Shh.
Stella.

473
00:30:53,650 --> 00:30:55,750
What on earth is Sam thinking?

474
00:30:55,750 --> 00:30:58,020
With all that's going on
in the world today,

475
00:30:58,020 --> 00:31:00,320
we don't need this kind of attention
focused on us.

476
00:31:00,330 --> 00:31:03,690
Well, he wasn't looking for it, Rose.
Irwin got him involved.

477
00:31:03,700 --> 00:31:09,100
Well, you tell him that everybody
is terrified by what this man did.

478
00:31:09,100 --> 00:31:11,370
Sophie Gittelson
fired her girl today.

479
00:31:11,370 --> 00:31:14,440
She's been with them
for 11 years.

480
00:31:14,440 --> 00:31:17,170
They fired Gladys?
Why? She's lovely.

481
00:31:17,180 --> 00:31:19,810
Yeah, she's lovely.

482
00:31:19,810 --> 00:31:22,380
But what if one of her relatives
comes to visit?

483
00:31:22,380 --> 00:31:24,110
They have their daughter
to think of.

484
00:31:24,120 --> 00:31:27,050
I would've done the same thing.

485
00:31:38,800 --> 00:31:41,200
Well, if it isn't
Mr. Friedlansky.

486
00:31:41,200 --> 00:31:43,000
Mr. Weisman.

487
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:46,800
Dora and I couldn't remember.
Were you born here or in Minsk?

488
00:31:46,810 --> 00:31:49,970
We, uh... We came over
when I was one.

489
00:31:49,980 --> 00:31:51,610
That's what I thought.

490
00:31:54,750 --> 00:31:57,880
So you feel like a really big shot, I bet,
defending that schvartze.

491
00:31:59,420 --> 00:32:02,250
What do you think
your father would say?

492
00:32:02,250 --> 00:32:04,150
I could not tell you.

493
00:32:07,490 --> 00:32:10,130
I think he'd say he was proud.

494
00:32:12,330 --> 00:32:13,800
For the defense.

495
00:32:15,230 --> 00:32:16,670
Don't mention it.

496
00:32:18,700 --> 00:32:20,240
To anyone.

497
00:32:42,860 --> 00:32:44,360
Eew!

498
00:32:53,800 --> 00:32:55,940
Jury selection, gentlemen.

499
00:32:55,940 --> 00:32:58,140
Clerk, call the first
venire person.

500
00:32:58,140 --> 00:33:00,510
Lester Gilman of Norwalk.

501
00:33:01,450 --> 00:33:03,710
Mr. Gilman.

502
00:33:10,090 --> 00:33:12,490
Mr., uh, Gilman,

503
00:33:12,490 --> 00:33:17,390
um, in this case a colored man is accused
of raping a white woman.

504
00:33:17,400 --> 00:33:19,960
Could you be fair
in deciding such a case?

505
00:33:21,230 --> 00:33:22,900
I think so.

506
00:33:22,900 --> 00:33:24,230
No further questions.

507
00:33:27,340 --> 00:33:29,310
Accepted by the defense.

508
00:33:29,310 --> 00:33:34,340
To tell you the truth, I don't know much
about them, the colored.

509
00:33:34,350 --> 00:33:36,710
We don't have too many
in Stratford.

510
00:33:47,420 --> 00:33:48,990
Excused.

511
00:33:54,100 --> 00:33:57,170
I'll be honest with you.
I don't like the colored.

512
00:33:57,170 --> 00:33:59,900
Seems to me they're always getting into
some sort of trouble.

513
00:34:01,010 --> 00:34:02,870
I don't think much
of Hebrews either.

514
00:34:04,140 --> 00:34:05,810
Excuse me?

515
00:34:05,810 --> 00:34:09,680
Well, you're one of them...
I figured.

516
00:34:11,380 --> 00:34:14,320
Thank you for your candor,
Mr. Wright.

517
00:34:14,320 --> 00:34:15,950
Uh, no further questions.

518
00:34:17,860 --> 00:34:19,220
Excuse for cause.

519
00:34:19,220 --> 00:34:21,160
Counselor?

520
00:34:21,160 --> 00:34:25,290
Your Honor, we move to have Mr. Wright
excused for cause.

521
00:34:25,300 --> 00:34:27,160
On what grounds?

522
00:34:27,170 --> 00:34:28,800
- Bias.
- I know.

523
00:34:28,800 --> 00:34:30,230
He just admitted he's biased.

524
00:34:31,670 --> 00:34:34,400
Mr. Wright, you are
a law-abiding citizen.

525
00:34:34,410 --> 00:34:36,670
Wouldn't you say?
That's right, Your Honor.

526
00:34:36,670 --> 00:34:41,910
If I instructed you that the law requires
that you set aside your bias,

527
00:34:41,910 --> 00:34:43,780
would you obey my instruction?

528
00:34:44,720 --> 00:34:46,180
Guess I'd have to.

529
00:34:46,180 --> 00:34:48,820
The challenge for cause
is overruled.

530
00:34:48,820 --> 00:34:50,550
You may use
the peremptory challenge.

531
00:34:50,560 --> 00:34:52,960
- Your Honor, with all due respect...
- I've made my ruling.

532
00:34:56,990 --> 00:34:59,260
Excused.

533
00:34:59,260 --> 00:35:01,430
Mr. Ellis,
you agree, do you not,

534
00:35:01,430 --> 00:35:05,200
that as a colored man you could not fairly
pass judgment on Mr. Spell.

535
00:35:05,200 --> 00:35:07,340
No, sir.

536
00:35:07,340 --> 00:35:09,770
You agree you could not be fair.

537
00:35:09,770 --> 00:35:13,140
No. What I mean is, yes, if he's guilty,
I'd have to convict him.

538
00:35:14,380 --> 00:35:16,750
I'll use a challenge.

539
00:35:16,750 --> 00:35:18,580
Object.

540
00:35:18,580 --> 00:35:20,520
On what basis?
Just do it.

541
00:35:20,520 --> 00:35:22,050
Uh, Your Honor, I object.

542
00:35:22,050 --> 00:35:24,020
Grounds?

543
00:35:24,020 --> 00:35:26,960
He can't use the challenge to discrim...

544
00:35:26,960 --> 00:35:28,790
I heard that,
Mr. Marshall.

545
00:35:28,790 --> 00:35:31,890
It's a peremptory challenge,
Mr. Friedman.

546
00:35:31,900 --> 00:35:34,030
The State may use it
for whatever reason it wants.

547
00:35:35,600 --> 00:35:38,070
Mr. Willis, you have four left.
The defense has one.

548
00:35:38,070 --> 00:35:40,140
What was the point of that?

549
00:35:40,140 --> 00:35:43,470
Every single time they discriminate,
we're going to object.

550
00:35:43,480 --> 00:35:45,910
Recognize it.
Now.

551
00:35:45,910 --> 00:35:48,540
Mrs. Richmond,
do you reside in Greenwich?

552
00:35:48,550 --> 00:35:50,680
Yes, Mr. Willis.
I do now.

553
00:35:51,950 --> 00:35:53,950
And if the State
proves its case,

554
00:35:53,950 --> 00:35:55,890
you could convict the defendant?

555
00:35:55,890 --> 00:35:58,350
Yes, of course I could.

556
00:36:00,090 --> 00:36:03,360
Thank you, Mrs. Richmond.
That's all I wanted to know.

557
00:36:09,770 --> 00:36:13,900
Mrs. Richmond, I notice you have
an accent.

558
00:36:13,910 --> 00:36:19,140
Really? Here I thought you were the one
with the accent, Mr. Friedman.

559
00:36:19,140 --> 00:36:20,380
Fair enough.

560
00:36:21,450 --> 00:36:23,410
Mrs. Richmond,

561
00:36:23,410 --> 00:36:25,310
where did you live
before moving here?

562
00:36:25,320 --> 00:36:27,250
Raleigh, North Carolina.

563
00:36:27,250 --> 00:36:30,320
But now you live in Greenwich.
Yes, that's right.

564
00:36:30,320 --> 00:36:33,190
So if you live in Greenwich,
you must have heard about this case.

565
00:36:33,190 --> 00:36:36,190
It's all anybody talks about.

566
00:36:36,190 --> 00:36:40,200
I assume, then, that you've come
to some sort of conclusion

567
00:36:40,200 --> 00:36:42,230
regarding the defendant's guilt
or innocence?

568
00:36:43,300 --> 00:36:45,300
You assume incorrectly.

569
00:36:45,300 --> 00:36:47,700
I don't have all the evidence,
now, do I?

570
00:36:47,710 --> 00:36:50,110
Have you met
Mrs. Strubing?

571
00:36:50,110 --> 00:36:53,640
In passing, at parties
and community events.

572
00:36:53,650 --> 00:36:56,150
I believe we belong
to the same club.

573
00:36:56,150 --> 00:36:58,980
Do you really think then,
Mrs. Richmond,

574
00:36:58,980 --> 00:37:02,890
that with all of these connections...
the club, the parties...

575
00:37:02,890 --> 00:37:05,490
that you could really
just set all of that aside?

576
00:37:05,490 --> 00:37:08,290
I don't see why not.

577
00:37:08,290 --> 00:37:11,430
Thank you.
No further questions.

578
00:37:14,900 --> 00:37:16,930
The State accepts
Mrs. Richmond.

579
00:37:18,400 --> 00:37:20,040
Your Honor...
What?

580
00:37:20,040 --> 00:37:21,540
No. Absolutely not.

581
00:37:21,540 --> 00:37:24,240
Mr. Friedman.

582
00:37:24,240 --> 00:37:28,140
Your Honor, may we have five minutes,
please?

583
00:37:30,980 --> 00:37:32,920
Fine with me, Your Honor.

584
00:37:32,920 --> 00:37:35,590
The court will recess
for exactly five minutes.

585
00:37:35,590 --> 00:37:37,990
But we're not gonna make a habit of this,
are we, counselor?

586
00:37:37,990 --> 00:37:40,560
No. No, of course not.
Thank you, Your Honor.

587
00:37:43,730 --> 00:37:46,600
We have one challenge left.
It was made for this woman.

588
00:37:46,600 --> 00:37:48,330
Just trust me on this.

589
00:37:48,330 --> 00:37:50,330
She's a Southerner.
Lives in the same town.

590
00:37:50,340 --> 00:37:52,100
Take her.
I'm not your goddamn puppet.

591
00:37:52,100 --> 00:37:53,740
I'm getting rid of her.

592
00:37:53,740 --> 00:37:57,070
She's smart, she's confident,
she resists authority.

593
00:37:57,080 --> 00:37:59,610
Did you see the way
she talked back to you?

594
00:37:59,610 --> 00:38:02,580
The other jurors will listen to her.
Which is exactly the problem.

595
00:38:02,580 --> 00:38:05,510
She knows Mrs. Strubing.
They run in the same social circles.

596
00:38:05,520 --> 00:38:07,450
And she doesn't
put her on a pedestal.

597
00:38:07,450 --> 00:38:10,450
Maybe Mrs. Strubing
is a drinker.

598
00:38:10,460 --> 00:38:14,290
Maybe she has a boyfriend in town.
This woman may know things.

599
00:38:14,290 --> 00:38:16,760
You are stabbing in the dark.

600
00:38:16,760 --> 00:38:19,700
Maybe, but this I do know.

601
00:38:19,700 --> 00:38:23,470
The one thing Southerners like her hate
more than the colored...

602
00:38:23,470 --> 00:38:25,330
arrogant Yankee pricks
like Willis.

603
00:38:26,640 --> 00:38:29,370
Were you watching her?

604
00:38:29,370 --> 00:38:32,610
She folded her arms and sat back
when Willis spoke.

605
00:38:32,610 --> 00:38:35,380
When you began, she opened up,

606
00:38:35,380 --> 00:38:38,910
leaned forward,
removed her glasses.

607
00:38:38,920 --> 00:38:41,150
These are signs.

608
00:38:41,150 --> 00:38:42,620
Signs of what?

609
00:38:43,720 --> 00:38:45,190
She likes you.

610
00:38:53,060 --> 00:38:55,100
No, my gl...
my glasses!

611
00:38:55,100 --> 00:38:56,870
I need my glasses.

612
00:39:02,270 --> 00:39:04,210
- Well, it's about time.
- Yeah.

613
00:39:12,650 --> 00:39:14,720
Mr. Friedman?

614
00:39:16,590 --> 00:39:18,420
The defendant
accepts Mrs. Richmond.

615
00:39:20,260 --> 00:39:21,920
Am I missing something?

616
00:39:21,930 --> 00:39:25,760
Mrs. Richmond, you've been accepted
by both of the parties

617
00:39:25,760 --> 00:39:29,330
and will serve as
our 12th and final juror.

618
00:39:29,330 --> 00:39:32,340
The evidence will begin tomorrow
morning at 10:00.

619
00:39:32,340 --> 00:39:35,670
Hey, hey! Hey, hey! Mr. Friedman!
Mr. Friedman.

620
00:39:35,670 --> 00:39:38,640
What do you have to say
about today's comments by the NAACP?

621
00:39:38,640 --> 00:39:41,610
- What comments?
- The press release by Walter White?

622
00:39:41,610 --> 00:39:43,980
He says that, "The Spell case
will show the world

623
00:39:43,980 --> 00:39:46,680
that a colored man cannot get a fair
trial in the United States of America."

624
00:39:46,680 --> 00:39:48,950
- Do you agree, Mr. Friedman?
- I have nothing to say about that.

625
00:39:48,950 --> 00:39:50,690
What about you,
Mr. Marshall?

626
00:39:50,690 --> 00:39:53,960
Hasn't it been proven
in this courtroom already?

627
00:39:56,560 --> 00:40:00,360
How can a man have a fair trial
when he's denied counsel of his choice?

628
00:40:00,370 --> 00:40:04,130
When the members of his race
are eliminated from service on his jury?

629
00:40:04,140 --> 00:40:08,200
When fear and bias against his race are the
central points of the case against him?

630
00:40:08,210 --> 00:40:10,370
In Europe right now,

631
00:40:11,840 --> 00:40:14,180
the forces of tyranny
have mobilized

632
00:40:14,180 --> 00:40:18,180
behind the vision
of a so-called master race.

633
00:40:18,180 --> 00:40:22,220
But here in America,
our differences aren't supposed to matter.

634
00:40:22,220 --> 00:40:26,320
Here we're promised
equal protection under the law.

635
00:40:26,320 --> 00:40:28,060
Separate but equal!

636
00:40:28,060 --> 00:40:30,160
Nothing complicated about that.

637
00:40:30,160 --> 00:40:34,760
That promise has not been realized,
not even close.

638
00:40:34,770 --> 00:40:39,100
Not in Birmingham, Alabama,
nor in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma,

639
00:40:39,100 --> 00:40:41,670
and certainly not here
in Bridgeport, Connecticut...

640
00:40:43,880 --> 00:40:47,810
where your bigotry is simply covered
by a northern accent.

641
00:40:50,180 --> 00:40:53,520
But a fair jury can always
render a just verdict.

642
00:40:53,520 --> 00:40:55,620
That's what we're striving for
here today.

643
00:40:55,620 --> 00:40:59,090
The Constitution was not written for us.
We know that.

644
00:40:59,090 --> 00:41:01,520
But no matter what,
we're gonna make it work for us.

645
00:41:01,530 --> 00:41:05,230
From now on
we claim it as our own.

646
00:41:23,110 --> 00:41:24,450
What's bothering you?

647
00:41:24,450 --> 00:41:26,050
Sam.
Not now.

648
00:41:26,050 --> 00:41:27,980
What's bothering me?

649
00:41:27,990 --> 00:41:31,150
You insulting the judge on the courthouse
steps. That's what's bothering me.

650
00:41:31,160 --> 00:41:34,220
Just relax.

651
00:41:34,230 --> 00:41:36,490
Excuse me?

652
00:41:36,490 --> 00:41:39,060
I have to live in this city
after you're gone. Understand?

653
00:41:39,060 --> 00:41:41,660
No more public statements
until this trial is over, or I'm gone.

654
00:41:41,670 --> 00:41:43,570
Let me make this clear.

655
00:41:43,570 --> 00:41:46,570
My people will decide what to say
to the newspapers and when to say it.

656
00:41:46,570 --> 00:41:48,940
The newspapers should have
no place in this trial.

657
00:41:48,940 --> 00:41:51,610
But they already do. People are losing
their jobs because of these stories.

658
00:41:51,610 --> 00:41:53,780
- Those people are not my clients!
- Well, they are mine!

659
00:41:53,780 --> 00:41:58,650
My jury isn't just the 12 people in that
jury box. It's the whole goddamn nation.

660
00:41:58,650 --> 00:42:01,490
You just focus on this
case, try your best not

661
00:42:01,500 --> 00:42:04,420
to screw it up and leave
the big picture to me.

662
00:42:04,420 --> 00:42:07,090
Sam.

663
00:42:07,090 --> 00:42:09,690
What is it, Irwin?
Don't you have something to do?

664
00:42:11,130 --> 00:42:13,100
There's someone waiting for you
in my office.

665
00:42:13,100 --> 00:42:15,300
Yes?
And who is this someone?

666
00:42:15,300 --> 00:42:17,370
Uh, Officer McCoy.

667
00:42:17,370 --> 00:42:20,140
And who the hell
is Officer McCoy?

668
00:42:20,140 --> 00:42:22,940
The cop who pulled Spell over
that night.

669
00:42:33,520 --> 00:42:35,380
I just did what you said.

670
00:42:35,390 --> 00:42:39,860
I drove around Port Chester,
pulling over police cars, and I found him.

671
00:42:39,860 --> 00:42:42,220
Attaboy, Irwin.
Attaboy.

672
00:42:42,230 --> 00:42:44,290
What time did you pull over
Mr. Spell?

673
00:42:48,060 --> 00:42:50,200
Did you hear the question?

674
00:42:52,040 --> 00:42:55,640
3:37 a.m.,
according to my notes.

675
00:42:57,540 --> 00:42:59,110
Why'd you stop him?

676
00:43:00,840 --> 00:43:02,280
It didn't look like...

677
00:43:03,810 --> 00:43:06,150
a man like that
would drive that car.

678
00:43:08,080 --> 00:43:09,950
Was anyone with him in the car?

679
00:43:11,190 --> 00:43:13,990
No. He was alone.

680
00:43:13,990 --> 00:43:16,430
You're willing to
testify to that in court?

681
00:43:16,430 --> 00:43:19,060
If I have to.

682
00:43:19,060 --> 00:43:23,100
Irwin, get a sworn statement from
Officer McCoy, then escort him out.

683
00:43:23,100 --> 00:43:24,630
Officer.

684
00:43:31,510 --> 00:43:32,910
Wow.

685
00:43:33,740 --> 00:43:35,310
An honest policeman.

686
00:43:40,920 --> 00:43:43,290
See what your publicity
stirs up?

687
00:43:43,290 --> 00:43:46,120
No, it just brings 'em out
where you can see 'em.

688
00:43:47,720 --> 00:43:49,460
Give us justice!

689
00:43:49,460 --> 00:43:51,490
That doesn't look
anything like me.

690
00:43:52,700 --> 00:43:54,160
Does it?

691
00:44:04,410 --> 00:44:07,210
The State of Connecticut
v. Joseph Spell.

692
00:44:07,210 --> 00:44:08,940
Are counsel ready to proceed?

693
00:44:08,950 --> 00:44:11,110
Ready for the State.

694
00:44:11,120 --> 00:44:12,720
We are, Your Honor.

695
00:44:12,720 --> 00:44:15,550
Mr. Willis, you may call
your first witness.

696
00:44:15,550 --> 00:44:18,820
The State calls Greenwich Police
Captain Burke to the stand.

697
00:44:27,900 --> 00:44:30,430
Would you identify these photos,
Captain Burke?

698
00:44:30,430 --> 00:44:32,970
Yes, sir.
That's the Kensico Reservoir.

699
00:44:34,340 --> 00:44:36,670
Did you find any evidence
at the scene

700
00:44:36,670 --> 00:44:38,310
that pertains to this case?

701
00:44:38,310 --> 00:44:40,910
Yes, sir, we did.

702
00:44:40,910 --> 00:44:43,650
We found Mrs. Strubing's sealskin coat
floating in the reservoir,

703
00:44:43,650 --> 00:44:46,080
under the bridge, about here.

704
00:44:46,080 --> 00:44:49,950
Then about here, on the guardrail,
we found some strands of fabric.

705
00:44:49,950 --> 00:44:52,450
I believe they were stuck
to some bird droppings.

706
00:44:52,460 --> 00:44:55,460
Were you able to
identify the fabric?

707
00:44:55,460 --> 00:44:59,330
Yes, sir. It matched the fabric
from Mrs. Strubing's sealskin coat.

708
00:45:01,700 --> 00:45:04,000
Thank you.
Nothing further.

709
00:45:06,140 --> 00:45:08,000
Your witness,
Mr. Friedman.

710
00:45:15,610 --> 00:45:17,110
Bird droppings.

711
00:45:18,010 --> 00:45:19,280
Sorry?

712
00:45:19,280 --> 00:45:22,990
Uh, bird droppings,
Captain Burke?

713
00:45:22,990 --> 00:45:24,420
Yes, that's right.

714
00:45:25,720 --> 00:45:28,320
Were you able to
identify the bird?

715
00:45:30,960 --> 00:45:33,300
May I?

716
00:45:33,300 --> 00:45:35,000
Thank you.

717
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:37,170
Now...

718
00:45:37,170 --> 00:45:41,700
on one side of the bridge is the reservoir,
placid as a lake.

719
00:45:41,710 --> 00:45:47,510
On the other side is a 30-foot drop
onto a jagged rock bed.

720
00:45:47,510 --> 00:45:49,810
- Is that correct?
- You could say that.

721
00:45:49,810 --> 00:45:53,080
And the fabric that you found
was on the lake side,

722
00:45:53,080 --> 00:45:55,480
right about here,

723
00:45:55,490 --> 00:45:57,550
around 60 feet onto the bridge.

724
00:45:57,560 --> 00:45:59,860
Sixty-seven feet,
four inches.

725
00:45:59,860 --> 00:46:01,890
Okay.

726
00:46:01,890 --> 00:46:07,660
Did you conclude, then, that Mrs. Strubing
fell or jumped off the bridge?

727
00:46:07,670 --> 00:46:11,100
- I concluded that she was pushed.
- Pushed?

728
00:46:11,100 --> 00:46:12,770
To murder her.

729
00:46:12,770 --> 00:46:14,600
That's right.

730
00:46:14,610 --> 00:46:19,170
As a trained
crime investigator, Captain,

731
00:46:19,180 --> 00:46:21,040
did you ever ask yourself,

732
00:46:21,050 --> 00:46:24,210
if someone wanted
Mrs. Strubing dead,

733
00:46:24,220 --> 00:46:28,550
why not push her onto the sharp, jagged
rock bed rather than the still lake water?

734
00:46:28,550 --> 00:46:31,420
Object.
Asking for speculation.

735
00:46:31,420 --> 00:46:34,960
Sustained. The jury will
disregard the question.

736
00:46:36,860 --> 00:46:39,900
Now...
Mrs. Strubing told you

737
00:46:39,900 --> 00:46:43,330
that after pushing her
into the water,

738
00:46:44,570 --> 00:46:46,800
Joseph threw rocks at her
from the bridge.

739
00:46:46,800 --> 00:46:48,740
Is that correct?
Yes.

740
00:46:48,740 --> 00:46:51,540
Mm-hmm.
Were there any rocks on the bridge?

741
00:46:52,640 --> 00:46:55,040
I don't know.
There may have been.

742
00:46:55,050 --> 00:46:57,950
But there were rocks in the area
around the bridge. Is that correct?

743
00:46:57,950 --> 00:46:59,620
Yes, there were.

744
00:46:59,620 --> 00:47:02,250
About how big were they?

745
00:47:02,250 --> 00:47:04,150
I really couldn't say.

746
00:47:09,390 --> 00:47:10,690
Were they...

747
00:47:12,600 --> 00:47:14,900
any bigger than this, Captain?

748
00:47:18,300 --> 00:47:20,200
I can't say they were.

749
00:47:28,580 --> 00:47:32,080
This... This is a pebble,
isn't it, Captain?

750
00:47:32,080 --> 00:47:33,880
You could call it that.

751
00:47:35,520 --> 00:47:36,820
What would you call it?

752
00:47:39,120 --> 00:47:40,660
A pebble.

753
00:47:43,490 --> 00:47:46,660
A pebble.

754
00:47:46,660 --> 00:47:50,830
So, in summary, Captain,

755
00:47:50,840 --> 00:47:53,640
it is your belief that this man

756
00:47:53,640 --> 00:47:57,870
threw Mrs. Strubing
into a placid lake,

757
00:47:57,880 --> 00:48:00,880
then gathered pebbles
to toss at her

758
00:48:00,880 --> 00:48:03,110
while she waited patiently
under the bridge.

759
00:48:03,110 --> 00:48:05,110
Object.

760
00:48:05,120 --> 00:48:07,220
Withdrawn.

761
00:48:07,220 --> 00:48:09,890
No further questions,
Your Honor.

762
00:48:09,890 --> 00:48:12,150
Captain Burke, you are excused.

763
00:48:12,160 --> 00:48:14,120
Court is adjourned.

764
00:48:14,120 --> 00:48:15,420
